WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:17.000
Welcome to the test set. Here we talk with some of the brightest thinkers and tinkerers in statistical analysis, scientific computing, and machine learning, digging into what makes them tick, plus the insights, experiments, and OMG moments that shape the field.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:27.000
This episode is part two of a conversation with Wes McKinney, open source software developer, author, metalhead, and principal architect at Posit.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:31.000
I'm Michael Chow. Thanks for joining us.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:50.000
I do feel like that's a theme that comes up too in a lot of your work and what you talk about is kind of the funding side, like how do we get people into this position? And I think, I feel like a lot of really interesting things you've said have also highlighted the kind of like, what gets attention and what doesn't.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:01:18.000
Well, the whole funding open source is a really complex question. I came initially from the finance world, and historically, folks from financial firms were not so keen to release open source software and maybe even less keen to fund work that might benefit their competitors.

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:32.000
So I recognize that a big part of being a successful open source developer is building a business case why people should adopt the software and why people should contribute to it.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:44.000
But then the next level beyond that is direct funding, and that often is even more complicated in part because of like, you know, kind of boring problems around budgeting and accounting and things like that.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:55.000
Because, you know, maybe the person who wants to fund the project, they want to fund the project, but they have to convince the powers that be to allocate budget to do the work.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:11.000
But, you know, I recognize that particularly with Arrow, because Arrow was a project that was much more resource intensive than Panda's, and it also needed to have broad buy-in from a lot of sectors of business.

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:22.000
And so I had to essentially embrace this role of being like a developer evangelist or like a chief marketing officer for the project.

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:26.000
You mean like why should you fund Arrow and kind of like how to?

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:45.000
Yeah, well there's the technical persuasion of convincing people that you have an approach to solving a problem that is the right one and that it is also solving a problem that they have and that they should consider adopting your experimental brand new technology, which, you know, not that many other people use.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:49.000
You're asking people to take a leap of faith.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:59.000
And so you have to identify people who have that maverick type innovator personality that are willing to take a risk, that they're willing to try something new.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:03.000
And, you know, they hope that it succeeds, but they're willing to fail.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:10.000
And so as an example, like early on in Arrow, like I connected with folks at Two Sigma.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:12.000
And they were like, we're really excited about this.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:22.000
And so we spent a bunch of time together and they were willing to, you know, put their money where their mouth is and put significant resources behind me to work on the project.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:34.000
You know, I think people have this idea that a lot of open source projects succeed on, you know, single passionate developer working nights and weekends, you know, squirreled away in the attic.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:35.000
Yeah.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:39.000
But the reality is that it does take, it takes a lot.

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:46.000
It takes, you know, you know, corporate resources like, you know, it's, it's, it takes a village essentially.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:59.000
And so I, you know, I couldn't have done, couldn't have done, you know, most of what I, what I've achieved without, you know, the support of people believing and, you know, believing in the different visions and, and experiments that I've run.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:04.000
Some of which have, you know, succeeded and, you know, some of that, you know, not everything has been successful.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:08.000
How did, I'm so curious how Apache factored in too.

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:17.000
Like I never, so I like know the name Apache and obviously a lot of the Apache, but I'm curious what was kind of the benefits you saw in the strategy.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:18.000
Right.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:21.000
The Apache Software Foundation or the ASF.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:25.000
So it's one of the best known open source foundations.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:28.000
They provide like a home for open source projects.

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:34.000
They provide like marketing and some developer infrastructure, legal protections.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:39.000
You know, they manage like trademark and copyright and that sort of thing, code licensing.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:43.000
They were started in the 1990s when the world of open source was very different.

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:53.000
So Linux was only a few years old at that time and everyone was freaked out about getting sued by Oracle or Sun or whoever were the major, you know, players in that day.

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:57.000
Because open source was just really as a thing was, was the free software movement.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:04:58.000
It was still, still very new.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:14.000
But as the ASF evolved, it has become essentially a neutral home for open source projects that have corporate contributors that are looking to establish a neutral, like a Switzerland like neutral ground for governance.

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:25.000
So that contributors can develop the project in a way that is open and transparent and to try to at least as much as possible mitigate some of their conflicts of interest.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:38.000
And so, you know, so when a company is looking to develop a project but to give up enough control where that maybe even their direct competitors can join as contributors.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:43.000
And, you know, you don't want to be looking around and say like what's your motivation or like what are you hiding?

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:46.000
Like, you know, what's going on in these backroom discussions?

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:54.000
So in the ASF, the rule is that you can't have, you can't make decisions in private or in backroom discussions.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:06:01.000
Like if you want to make a decision, you have to have the discussion openly and in public in a way where everybody can participate.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:04.000
And so this, this helps level the playing field.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:07.000
But it also helps people who maybe don't work at your company.

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:15.000
It gives them visibility into how you're thinking, what you're doing, why you're doing it and gives them a way to also get involved.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:22.000
And so as a way to build community, I think the ASF has played, played a pretty, you know, pretty important role.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:30.000
It sounds like Apache like really establishes like a place for companies or like, like you mentioned, like competitors to kind of trust.

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:32.000
Open source is an interesting one.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:39.000
Whereas I guess I've often as an open source developer thought mostly about as far as like the licensing.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:42.000
It's interesting to hear like all the other factors.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:47.000
So ASF is a combination of a permissive license that's corporate friendly.

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:53.000
So the Apache 2.0 license includes, you know, do whatever you like with the software, but also don't sue us.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:57.000
And like don't get, don't get software patents and then sue us over the software patents.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:08.000
So it has protections like for all of those, all of those things to make the corporate, you know, pointy haired lawyers happy that their bases are covered with respect to IP.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:17.000
But yeah, it's like, but beyond the licensing, there's just this community, community over code is like the motto of the ASF.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:26.000
Like this sort of community first mindset of like how you communicate, how you make decisions, how you treat each other, like having a code of conduct, being respectful.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:33.000
And, but how you, how you treat each other is also like, you know, that, that you treat people with respect in terms of like, you know,

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:39.000
you don't just show up and like try to steamroll a poll request or say like, you know, I'm the authority on this matter.

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:41.000
And this is the way that I think it should be done.

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:48.000
You actually have to argue from first principles why your approach to the problem is, you know, is the right one.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:55.000
So there's no like project dictator, you know, benevolent dictator for life, or there's no like explicit hierarchy within a project.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:08:00.000
Like if you have commit access to a project, your commit access cannot be taken away.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:14.000
So it's a very egalitarian and I think, I think a pretty successful model that other, other projects that don't, aren't necessarily in the ASF for whatever reason have, have, you know, have strived to, to emulate that, emulate that model.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:24.000
But I had almost no exposure to, to this way of working in open source until, you know, circa 2015 when I, when I ended up at Cloudera.

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:34.000
And so I think that was interesting because it was a combination of like seeing how ASF projects work, but then also exposure to big enterprise software.

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:43.000
Because I had lots of colleagues at Cloudera who had worked for VMware or for Google or for, I guess, Meta, Microsoft, like worked for all these big tech companies.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:55.000
And so I also, you know, having come from the finance world, which, you know, software engineering wise is a little bit more of the wild west and, and coming to more of like this highly, you know, enterprise corporate software engineering culture.

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:57.000
So it was very, it was very eye opening experience.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:05.000
I think that's definitely, you know, helped, helped me, you know, help me become a better software engineer.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:12.000
Or at least thinking about how to build larger software projects and enable them to scale in a way that's more, in a way that scale that's more healthy.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:14.000
What kind of stuff are you up to now?

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:19.000
Like I know a little bit about your stuff on the Positron team that I'm curious to hear about.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:20.000
Yeah, yeah.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:21.000
I know you're up to a lot more.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:27.000
Well, I mean, it was just, it was just around the time that I was learning about, you know, the ASF and we decided to start the Arrow project.

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:33.000
And, you know, that's when I first got involved with, got involved with Posit.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:36.000
So I'd known Hadley for, I'd known Hadley Wickham for several years.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:40.000
And Hadley just happened to be in town the month that we were, that we were launching Arrow.

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:42.000
And I was really excited about it.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:43.000
Oh, we're starting this new thing.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:47.000
And the idea is to have portable interoperable data frames.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:53.000
And so we spent a day together and brainstormed like what could we do with this that could be useful for the data science community.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:58.000
And so we decided to create a small, you know, small file format called Feather.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:02.000
So that was my first concrete collaboration with Hadley.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:04.000
And I think that was pretty successful.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:14.000
And it also helped demonstrate the potential of sharing, the potential of sharing technology between, across the language fences.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:21.000
And we were like how can we build tools that could help maybe, you know, tear down the language walls and end some of the language wars.

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:35.000
And so that kind of sent me down this path of just being, thinking a lot about how to build tools and systems that empower polyglot teams and polyglot, polyglot development.

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:39.000
So I spent, I've spent the better part of a decade working on, working on the Arrow project,

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:46.000
which has been all about building composable, modular, interoperable technologies that can be used across,

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:52.000
used interchangeably across programming languages and that can be mixed and matched to build different types of data processing systems.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:11:03.000
I was, you know, catching up with, catching up with, you know, JJ and the, JJ Allaire and founder of Posit and the Posit team.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:07.000
And so I was like, what's, you know, what's new at, what's new at Posit?

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:11.000
And like, oh, we're building a new polyglot data science IDE called Positron.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:13.000
And this was, this was in 2023.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:17.000
So this was all, you know, under NDA, like, you can't talk about this.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:25.000
And I, I found the, the idea of like, you know, taking all the, everything that, that Posit, formerly RStudio,

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:30.000
had learned about building an amazing data science user experience in a IDE form factor.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:35.000
So code first, you know, code editor, console, variables pane, plots pane.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:40.000
And re-imagining that within the context of the modern programming landscape,

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:45.000
which is very dominated by VS code and the VS code extension ecosystem.

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:49.000
And so at that point, Positron had been in, you know,

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:52.000
developed privately for a year and a half or so.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:56.000
And the prospect of getting involved in that and also, you know,

00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:01.000
getting involved in Posit's Python strategy more broadly really, really appealed to me.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:08.000
Because, you know, Posit had been RStudio and had been focused on the R, R, on the, on the, on R programming.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:12.000
Had rebranded Deposit, added Python support to all of its products,

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:17.000
started making, you know, significant contributions in the Python landscape, and hired you.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:18.000
Sure. Yeah.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:19.000
You know.

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:20.000
Which I'm glad for.

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:22.000
Yeah. Starting, you know, yeah, new projects.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:27.000
And as well as like bringing some of the goodness from the, from the R world into the Python world.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:32.000
You know, shiny, great tables, you know, lots of, lots of good stuff.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:36.000
And so, you know, I never imagined myself working on an IDE,

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:39.000
but I found some things in Positron.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:47.000
For example, you know, building a modern data viewer, like data explorer component.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:52.000
I imagined myself like, what do I want if I have data frames in memory?

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:56.000
Like, what do I want a data viewer, a data explorer component to do?

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:57.000
Yeah.

00:12:57.000 --> 00:13:01.000
And so we set about to try to build that thing, and it's still early,

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:06.000
but it's already a very useful thing that I enjoy using on a, you know, nearly daily basis.

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:10.000
And just as a decision on data viewer, is it, if I'm going to say it's like a,

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:17.000
it's basically like if I'm analyzing data, and this is like a cat doing data analysis.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:21.000
I'm analyzing my data, and I like have a data frame.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:24.000
A really common activity I want to do is like just peek at it,

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:27.000
and like interact, and kind of see what I've got.

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:28.000
Is that right?

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:35.000
So like a data viewer is like a really fast kind of like glimpse into your data that you can like filter.

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:39.000
And so we, as we, you know, initially brainstormed on it,

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:42.000
like because RStudio has a data viewer component.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:44.000
So when you have a data frame loaded up in RStudio,

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:47.000
you can click on the data frame in the variables pane,

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:49.000
and it will pop open this data viewer window.

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:53.000
It has some basic filtering capabilities.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:55.000
It has some search capabilities.

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:58.000
But so we started from that place.

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:02.000
We're like, well, we'd like to essentially have table stakes,

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:06.000
like deliver what exists in RStudio, but also sky's the limit.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:07.000
What else can we build?

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:08.000
What have we always dreamed of?

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:10.000
What have we always dreamed of having?

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:16.000
And so, you know, for me, like so often I've found myself looking at the data

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:20.000
while I'm writing code to clean it and manipulate it.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:26.000
And so I wanted to have the thing that I could apply selective filters,

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:29.000
or I could sort, or I could search,

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:34.000
but that would live update while I'm writing code and modifying the data set.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:37.000
And so I wanted that like live update experience.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:42.000
I want something that has really smooth, infinite scroll, both horizontally and vertically.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:47.000
I've often found myself with these like massive, you know, 10,000 column or 100,000 column data sets.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:53.000
I'm like, why can't we have a data explorer that is infinitely scrollable horizontally and vertically?

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:54.000
Sure.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:55.000
Why not?

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:56.000
I like that you just get to.

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:59.000
Yeah, so we built that thing.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:05.000
And of course, you know, seeing some of the innovations that have come out of the business intelligence world,

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:10.000
having things like, you know, spark lines, you know, summary statistics,

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:15.000
like being able to have like the statistical visualizations like just immediately available.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:20.000
We're really influenced by, you know, I'm a big fan of this tool called RealData.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:24.000
So it's Mike Driscoll's kind of latest company powered by DuckDB.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:28.000
But I also want to like really basic stuff like, you know, when you're in data,

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:33.000
if you're in VS Code and I'm sure you've been in VS Code and you have like a data file,

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:36.000
like shouldn't you be able to just open the data file and look at it?

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:39.000
So I wanted that like instant preview experience.

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:43.000
And so like we use DuckDB to build that.

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:48.000
You can just click on a parquet file and it opens and everything works.

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:51.000
And it's, you know, it's a really big parquet file.

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:56.000
It may not be instantaneous, but it's really snappy.

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:58.000
And so I'm proud of what we build.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:02.000
And it's a nice feeling, you know, to cross over,

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:05.000
to build something that's at the intersection of like backend engineering

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:08.000
because there's clearly like a lot of like, you know,

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:12.000
you need to have knowledge of the internals of like how Pandas works and how Polars works.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:13.000
Yeah.

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:18.000
And our data frames and how DuckDB works to create this thing that you can deliver

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:22.000
that snappy kind of intuitive thing, something that's easy to use but also is fast.

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:23.000
Yeah.

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:27.000
But yeah, now having something that I, you know, I just know is there

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:30.000
and I can pick up and use whenever I have data files is really nice.

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:31.000
Yeah, that's cool.

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:32.000
Yeah, it is funny.

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:35.000
I do feel like data viewers, it's like this funny, like in the abstract,

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:39.000
it's such a funny concept where you're like, it's a grid.

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:40.000
I can scroll it a lot.

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:41.000
It's got my data.

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:45.000
And I feel like it's one of those things where, well, like working on,

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:48.000
because I work a lot on tables, like how to display tables.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:54.000
I don't know if you've seen, I feel like tables seem like a really bizarre thing to focus on.

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:59.000
But like I do feel like with these data viewers, it's like when it hits,

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:00.000
it like just really hits.

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:05.000
Like as it turns out, it's like a real kind of load bearing.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:10.000
I mean, you spend a lot of time looking at data.

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:17.000
And now I think what's interesting is that now we have LLMs.

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:21.000
And like LLMs also need to be able to look at data.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:25.000
And they need to be able to look at a lot of data.

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:28.000
And context windows are only so big.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:31.000
So it may not be practical to take the whole data frame

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:34.000
and stuff it in a context window.

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:41.000
And so clearly like I think the focus of Positron and this data explorer

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:45.000
is empowering humans to be able to get the information that you need quickly

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:49.000
and intuitively and for it to be fast and like not get in your way.

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:55.000
But then, you know, also like as time goes on, like we have to think about, you know,

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:58.000
we have to think about the role of, you know,

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:06.000
how we expose information about data sets to the LLMs so that they also can, you know,

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:09.000
if they're empowering you to ask more questions, that they can get the information

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:12.000
they need to give you high quality suggestions.

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:15.000
So that's something I've been thinking about.

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:20.000
And I'm sure like, you know, like any data tool is going to be,

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:24.000
any data analysis environment is going to be asking themselves similar questions.

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:28.000
I'm also so curious with the data, you're talking about the data viewer and stuff,

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:30.000
what your day looks like?

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:36.000
Like what's the breakdown of how often are you like hands on keyboard coding

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:41.000
versus like emailing people or like nudging communities?

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:44.000
Like what is your day breakdown?

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:47.000
Mostly I've been working on, I've been working on Positron lately.

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:52.000
And since I work closely with folks who specialize in front-end development

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:56.000
and sometimes I find myself bottlenecked on, like I need help from somebody

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:58.000
who knows front-end better than I do.

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:02.000
Or if I try to do the front-end portion, I'll make a mess.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:08.000
And so it's a good ebb and flow in that like I might have a week where, you know,

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:14.000
I work mostly on Positron and, you know, have 10 pull requests or something.

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:18.000
And then a week where maybe I'm at a conference or like I'm, you know,

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:22.000
joining customer calls or like doing presentations.

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:26.000
Like actually I think one of the great things about being back at Posit

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:31.000
is having more input from real data science users.

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:36.000
Like learning from people who are using data science, open source data science

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:38.000
in a business setting.

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:43.000
Because I've been so heads down working on, just working on open source projects.

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:47.000
And, you know, I had my, you know, I was full-time at a startup, you know,

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:49.000
up until a year and a half ago.

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:51.000
So didn't have a lot of time to like go interview, you know,

00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:55.000
people working on enterprise data science teams to learn about like what their

00:19:55.000 --> 00:19:56.000
big problems are.

00:19:56.000 --> 00:19:58.000
So that's been really interesting.

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:03.000
And I do spend, I spend a portion of my time, spend a portion of my time investing.

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:09.000
Like I have, like I part-time, I have a, like a small venture fund which is

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:12.000
basically, you know, started out as an extension of the angel investing

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:14.000
that I was already doing.

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:20.000
But also it helps me be like, help be, not only, but help be Posit's eyes

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:24.000
and ears in the broader market and understand like, you know,

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:28.000
where technology trends are going.

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:31.000
Like what, you know, new companies, like what, you know, what they're doing.

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:33.000
You know, what can we learn from?

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:34.000
What should we do differently?

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:37.000
You know, where are there opportunities, things that we should be doing

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:38.000
that we're not doing?

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:41.000
And so that's been, you know, that's been interesting as well.

00:20:41.000 --> 00:20:45.000
I don't, I do not aspire to be a full-time, full-time venture investor.

00:20:45.000 --> 00:20:46.000
People are asking me that all the time.

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:48.000
Like I was just at a conference last week.

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:50.000
They're like, Wes, like you're a VC now?

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:51.000
I'm like, no, no.

00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:55.000
Like I'm at best, I'm at best a super angel.

00:20:55.000 --> 00:21:00.000
And my hope is, especially I've really focused on working with companies

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:05.000
that are directly involved in areas that I care about, like data infrastructure,

00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:09.000
developer tools, open source, things relating to open source data science.

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:12.000
And now some of the crossover into the AI landscape.

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:16.000
And so I'm hoping in helping, picking companies to work with

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:19.000
that they're building stuff or they're engaging with communities

00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:22.000
that I care about and that helps enrich the whole, you know,

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:25.000
make the whole pie bigger for everyone.

00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:28.000
I like the, like not looking to do it full-time.

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:35.000
And in a way I feel like you're like, I simply like code and organize and do this.

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:37.000
It's like maybe the more intense version.

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:38.000
Right, yeah.

00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:47.000
Essentially it's another lever in the community development sort of toolbox in a sense.

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:51.000
If you work with a company, you know, I've been an advisor,

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:56.000
like I'm an advisor for Lance DB, for example, which is Chong's new company.

00:21:56.000 --> 00:22:01.000
So he co-founded Lance DB with Lei from Cloudera.

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:05.000
So they're building, you know, a vector database and a file format

00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:09.000
for multimodal, you know, machine learning AI workloads.

00:22:09.000 --> 00:22:12.000
And that's like the perfect example of like they're using Arrow,

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:15.000
like they're using Data Fusion, like which came out of the Arrow ecosystem.

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:21.000
And so it's like, you know, their success is like the success of the Arrow ecosystem.

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:26.000
And that benefits the data science world more broadly.

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:31.000
I'm so curious to ask you, because I know last year we were both in Charleston

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:36.000
and we went to a metal bar.

00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:41.000
And in fact, someone in a review called it like a relatively new metal bar

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:45.000
that hadn't gotten its patina, its metal bar patina.

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:49.000
And I remember asking like, who listened to metal?

00:22:49.000 --> 00:22:53.000
And we had one very obviously metal coworker.

00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:57.000
And I feel like you really surprised us by coming out of the woodwork.

00:22:57.000 --> 00:23:02.000
I figured this is our chance for you to maybe tell the people about your,

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:06.000
what do you love, what's hot, what's not in metal for you?

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:13.000
Well, I definitely have like wide ranging and at times eclectic music tastes.

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:16.000
But I do enjoy.

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:21.000
When I was in college, I had a number of friends who were big metal heads

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:26.000
and they introduced me to symphonic and power metal.

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:30.000
And so recently the last metal show I saw was Dream Theater.

00:23:30.000 --> 00:23:32.000
They played Nashville.

00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:33.000
It was awesome.

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:35.000
I think the second time that I've seen them.

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:39.000
And so I wouldn't say I listen to too much metal these days.

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:45.000
Maybe I ran the half marathon in San Francisco several years ago

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:48.000
and my playlist was mostly metal.

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:50.000
I think it really helped.

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:56.000
I really enjoy the concerts, especially the live concerts,

00:23:56.000 --> 00:24:01.000
just because I think the crowd energy is amazing.

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:06.000
But also I appreciate the technical execution.

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:09.000
Just the playing is just incredible.

00:24:09.000 --> 00:24:16.000
Everything, the singers, the drummers, all of the guitar and bass.

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:20.000
They put on really technically impressive shows.

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:25.000
Power metal is pretty epic.

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:28.000
I guess Dragon Force is the one a lot of people.

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:35.000
Yeah, they're kind of the most over the top.

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:36.000
I do like Dragon Force.

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:37.000
I saw them once in concert.

00:24:37.000 --> 00:24:40.000
It was pretty insane.

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:43.000
A band that I really liked was Sabaton.

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:45.000
They're Swedish.

00:24:45.000 --> 00:24:50.000
They do a lot of war themed music.

00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:53.000
It's all a crowd energy thing.

00:24:53.000 --> 00:24:55.000
I didn't even know them.

00:24:55.000 --> 00:25:00.000
I went to see them in San Francisco with a former colleague from Cloudera.

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:04.000
I was there to see Nightwish, which is a famous symphonic metal band from Finland.

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:07.000
It's been around since the late 90s.

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:09.000
Sabaton was the opener.

00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:13.000
I realized pretty quickly, everyone's here to see Sabaton.

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:16.000
They're not here to see the main show.

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:21.000
I think we were also blown away by the opener.

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:23.000
Nightwish was still great.

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:24.000
They're always great.

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:29.000
It was almost a little bit of a let down.

00:25:29.000 --> 00:25:34.000
My fellow metal heads, keep it real.

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:41.000
I guess my last question is, are you ever positron, data viewer, Sabaton, let's go?

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:49.000
For coding music, it needs to be a little more chill.

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:52.000
I do like having something on in the background.

00:25:52.000 --> 00:25:57.000
I got to listen to music without lyrics, I found.

00:25:57.000 --> 00:26:05.000
I found movie soundtracks and soundtracks to video games have been pretty successful.

00:26:05.000 --> 00:26:08.000
Coding background music.

00:26:08.000 --> 00:26:11.000
It varies by the day and my mood and whatnot.

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:12.000
I love it.

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:14.000
Well, Wes, thanks so much for chatting.

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:15.000
I mean, we're co-hosts.

